<h2><u>April 13, 2005</u></h2>

<br>
<div class="title">F For Fake</div>
<p>What would it take to build an <strong>Academy of Fake News</strong>? Perhaps a <strong>Fake News Hall of Fame</strong> would suffice. And who would our inductees be?</p>

<p>The print world would supply the first round of usual suspects -- <em>The Onion</em>, <em>Spy</em>, and maybe <em>Might</em>. And then television would be recognized -- <em>The Daily Show</em> would arrive in the second round; <em>SNL</em>'s "Weekend Update" would get some sort of lifetime achievement award. Our mythical academy would confront its first crisis when Michael Moore suggests that films (particularly those <em>controversy du jour</em> quasi-autobiographical documentaries) deserve notation in our hallowed corridors. Overnight, our Hall of Fame would be derided as a sell-out when  <em>The Blair Witch Project</em> is chosen as the first film to be inducted. Angry traditionalists would argue that the fake canon started with Orson Welles' <em>F for Fake</em>.</p>

<p>All of that fake preamble is a setup to point out that <a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B0007M2234/"><em>F For Fake</em></a> is being released on DVD next month. Postmodern before there was such a thing, <em>Fake</em> is a rocket ride though great art forgeries, Howard Hughes biographies, and fact versus fiction conundrums. Long overdue to DVD, this fake classic is being released by Criterion on April 26.</p>

<br>
<div class="title">Insert <em>Onion</em> Headline Here</div>
<p>Since fake news has become its own legitimate segment of the media industry (<em>because I said so, that's why</em>), <em>The Onion</em> should consider self-parody. A fake story of a fake news organization would be perfect. Borrow liberally from the <a href="http://www.sptimes.com/2005/04/12/Floridian/Peeling_the_Onion.shtml" target="_blank">new <em>Onion</em> profile</a> in the <em>SP Times</em>.</p>

